TEXT(beginproblem());

##############################################################
#
#  Setup
#
#

Context("Numeric");
#given
$m = random(70, 90, 5);
$g = 9.81;
$B = random(150, 250, 50);
$v = random(70, 90, 5);


#computation
$r = 2*$B;
$rdot = 0;
$rdotdot = -$B*( ($v/$r)**2 );
$theta = 0;
$thetadot = $v/$r;
$Fseat = $m*$g - ($m)*( $rdotdot - $r*($thetadot**2) );


$imagescale = 0.8;
$width = $imagescale*1059;
$height = $imagescale*888;
#set tolerance
Context()->flags->set(
tolerance=>.05,
tolType=>'relative');

##############################################################
#
#  PGML 
#
#

BEGIN_PGML

You are standing on the ground watching an aerobatics show, where a plane is performing a vertical loop. The beginning of the loop can be modelled by a cardioid, [`r = [$B](1 + cos(\theta))`] [`m`], where [`\theta`] is in radians. At the bottom of the loop (A), the pilot's speed is a constant [`[$v]`] [`m/s`].

What is the vertical reaction force on the pilot by the plane, at point A, if the pilot's mass is [`[$m]`] [`kg`]?

(Assume [`g = 9.81 m/s^2`], use [`v = \sqrt{(\dot{r})^2 + (r\dot{\theta})^2}`] to find [`\dot{\theta}`]).


[@ image( "21-P-FA-GD-013.png", width=>[$width], height=>[$height]) @]*


[`F_{seat} =`]  [_____]{"$Fseat"} [`N`]

END_PGML

